Generate lists of human genes biased by the number of transcripts for the genes.

Use a gene info file derived from a gtf file from Ensembl containing all the genes and transcripts in the human genome.



This table show the number of times that a gene name appears in the genome annotated as a distinct gene.
There are lots of duplicate gene names so well use the Ensembl gene IDs for the initial processing.
The gene set files that we use for the GO analysis do not contain Ensembl IDs so well have to convert back to gene name at the point when we run the GO analysis.

The highly duplicated gene names probably arent in the GO annotations much but itd be worth checking.

There are 0 duplicate Ensembl IDs so well use these for filtering and convert back to gene name at the end of this analysis.

Number of transcripts per gene


Thresholds



Thresholds based on the distribution of the data at 90th, 95th and 99th percentiles.

Generating the biased gene sets and running the GO analysis


1. Randomly select 200 genes from the subset of genes with high/very high/very very high numbers of transcripts.

2. Run functional enrichment analysis, record results.

3. Repeat steps 1 and 2 100 times.

Repeat this for each transcript category.



The table shows the number of functional enrichment analyses that returned 1 or more significantly enriched categories from the 100 that were run.




The violin plot shows the number of significant categories per gene list returned from the GO analysis.

Identified categories

The number of times that a functional category was identified from the 100 times that the analysis was run for each bias category. The table contains every functional category that appeared once or more in any of the bias categories.

In total, 1689 functional categories appeared at least once.

Filter Categories

We dont want categories that only appeared a handful of times so well use an arbitrary value of 20 as a threshold.

GO category occurrences

Deduplicate terms

There are functional categories that were identified in all 3 transcript categories and 66 functional categories identified in 2 transcript categories. The duplicate terms will be removed from the more stringent categories.
